<TR>
    <TD WIDTH="20%" ALIGN="center"><FONT FACE="Arial"><BR><IMG SRC="images/hate/kkk_blood_drop.jpg" WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=135 BORDER=1 ALIGN="MIDDLE" ALT="Image by Antonio Martins"><BR>The Blood Drop Flag<BR><BR><IMG SRC="images/hate/kkk_blood_drop_v2.gif" WIDTH=216 HEIGHT=144 BORDER=1 ALIGN="MIDDLE" ALT="Image by Tomislav Todorovic"><BR>The Duke Flag<BR><BR><IMG SRC="images/hate/kkk2.gif" ALT="Image by Tomislav Todorovic" WIDTH="216" HEIGHT="145" BORDER="1"><BR>The Sun Wheel Flag<BR><BR></TD>
	<TD WIDTH="80%" VALIGN="top"><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="+1">Knights of the Ku Klux Klan (USA)</FONT></B>
	<P><FONT FACE="Arial">The Blood Drop symbol is most often used by various Klan organizations throughout the United States.  Usually at clan rallies there are actually a lot more United States Flags displayed than KKK flags, despite their very un-American racial beliefs.</P>
	<P><FONT FACE="Arial">The Ku Klux Klan was established in Tennessee in 1866. Most of the leaders were former members of the Confederate Army and the first Grand Wizard was Nathan Forrest, a confederate general during the American Civil War. In the late 1800s and early 1900s Clansmen wearing masks, white cardboard hats and draped in white sheets, have been responsible for torturing and killing black Americans and sympathetic whites.  The Civil Rights movement of the 1960s prompted a modern rebirth of the Ku Klux Klan activities that has persisted until the present day.</P>
